Les deux Pologne
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
An old leader of Solidarity, an ex-political prisoner, and a former foreign minister - who led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another declaration stating that he was not a secret police agent during communism.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's behavior, and Geremek stated that the lustration law [decommunization] poses a threat to public liberties.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and inciting anti-Polish feelings.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision dated May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament for now.
But this law is part of a broader policy of the Polish government aimed at weakening institutions and democratic structures in the country.
What is happening in Poland, where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a fight for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best within him, while the second liberates the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into secrecy when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika."
In the negotiations that brought an end to the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that opened the way to the peaceful dismantling of communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful victors and oppressed losers.
<since> 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. Even the former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
<but> not everyone has followed this path.
<today>, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity vengefuls, post-communist troublemakers, xenophobic and antisemitic groups, heirs of pre-war chauvinism, and circles around Radio Maryja, the voice of ethnic-clerical fundamentalism.
<everywhere>, there are worrying signs: the authority of Justice is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is questioned, civil servants are bought off, and the role of the prosecutor is politicized.
<every day>, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more crime, the market economy but also the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced fear of foreigners and fear of a massive Western cultural invasion.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the State, but it took care of them.
In a world of freedom, no one takes care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the government in place governs, combining the conservative elixir of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But among the communists, the guilty have not been punished, and the virtuous activists of Solidarity have not been rewarded.
Thus, a sense of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed against both former enemies and old allies who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest success in 300 years.
To them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland needed a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be redressed.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a great purge.
According to preliminary estimates, the lustration will take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the security services' archives; it will be made public.
The 700,000 people promised lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.

The cardinal of Kraków, Dziwisz, reminds us that there is "no room for revenge, retribution, disrespect for human dignity, and unfounded accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, whether confirmed or not, of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would neither be part of NATO nor the European Union.
Today, two Poles are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance fights against the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, that of Pope John Paul II and Czeslaw Milosz, of my friends from the underground and prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Polish people will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The constitutional court decision leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will neither destroy what gave birth to it, the will for freedom, nor what it has produced, a democratic state.
